;; ch09-scrolling-and-parallax.book.slatl
;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 9: Scrolling and Parallax

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      9
  :title               "Scrolling and Parallax"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :draws-from-preserved (:book "book-of-games-preserved" :ch 13 :ch 14)
  :prose
"Two-dimensional games learned to feel three-dimensional before there
was a Z-axis. The trick is parallax. When you drive down a road, the
fencepost right next to you flies past your window; the mountain on the
horizon barely moves; the sun in the sky doesn't move at all. Your brain
computes depth from the difference in apparent motion.

Video games discovered this in the mid-1980s. A shoot-em-up with a
starfield background moving at half speed felt vast. A jungle-runner
with grass in front, trees behind, mountains further behind, sky
behind that — each moving at its own rate — felt like flying through
a WORLD, not walking a screen.

This chapter builds a three-layer parallax scene. Foreground grass at
1.0×, mid-hills at 0.5×, distant mountains at 0.2×. The camera pans as
the player runs, and the layers pan at different rates, and the world
gains depth. Same tile grid we built in chapter 8; different rules for
how the background paints.

---

## 9.1 The near layer

Start with just the foreground — camera-follow motion.

```scheme
;; Player runs right; foreground grass follows the camera exactly.
(define (near-only)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 60 1 32 20 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  ;; A row of grass tiles that scroll 1:1 with the camera.
  (scene/grid 'grass 60 1 32 8 0 192)
  (world/each 'grass
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 8)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 1920 240)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
       (world/each 'grass
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'grass (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 8)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32)))))

(big-bang near-only)
```

Nothing new — everything scrolls with the camera at rate 1.0×.
Walking right, all tiles slide left across the screen at the same
rate the player moves.

---

## 9.2 Add a slower layer

Now for the depth. We paint hills that scroll at HALF the camera rate.

```scheme
;; Foreground scrolls at 1.0x; mid-hills at 0.5x.
(define (two-layer-parallax)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 60 1 32 20 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 1920 240)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       ;; The camera is at some world position; get x-component.
       (let ((cam-x (car (world/camera))))
         ;; Mid-hills: 5 hill sprites, each 64 wide, at y = 140.
         ;; Their apparent x = world-x - camera-x * 0.5
         ;; So we paint them at (world-x - cam-x * 0.5).
         (let loop ((i 0))
           (when (< i 5)
             (let ((world-hill-x (* i 200))
                   (screen-hill-x (- (* i 200) (* cam-x 0.5))))
               ;; Only paint if visible.
               (when (and (> screen-hill-x -64) (< screen-hill-x 384))
                 (paint-cell 'hill (+ screen-hill-x cam-x) 140 64 40)))
             (loop (+ i 1)))))
       (world/each 'ground
                   (lambda (t)
                     (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32)))))

(big-bang two-layer-parallax)
```

Read the middle-layer paint math carefully.

The camera is at world-x `cam-x`. Normally, an object at world-x `wx`
appears on screen at `wx - cam-x`. But for a parallax layer at rate
0.5, we want the object to appear on screen at `wx - cam-x * 0.5` —
half as much offset. Since `paint-cell` subtracts the camera under the
hood, we PASS a world-x of `screen-x + cam-x` — which becomes
`(wx - cam-x * 0.5) + cam-x = wx + cam-x * 0.5`, so `paint-cell`
displays it at `(wx + cam-x * 0.5) - cam-x = wx - cam-x * 0.5`. That's
the parallax we wanted.

Simpler mental model: 'draw each layer as if the camera moved at
(1 - rate) times its actual speed.'

The mid-hills drift half as fast as the ground. Kids running right
see the hills slide slowly. Their brain interprets: hills are far
away. No Z-axis needed.

---

## 9.3 Three layers

Add distant mountains and sky.

```scheme
;; Three parallax layers: sky (0), mountains (0.2), hills (0.5),
;; plus foreground (1.0).
(define (three-layer-parallax)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 60 1 32 20 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 1920 240)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -10))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (let ((cam-x (car (world/camera))))
         ;; Sky — doesn't scroll. Just paint at absolute (0, 0).
         (paint-cell 'sky (+ 160 cam-x) 40 320 80)
         ;; Distant mountains — 5 sprites at 0.2x rate.
         (let loop ((i 0))
           (when (< i 6)
             (paint-cell 'mountain
                         (+ (* i 200) (* cam-x 0.2)) 100 100 60)
             (loop (+ i 1))))
         ;; Mid hills — 5 sprites at 0.5x rate.
         (let loop ((i 0))
           (when (< i 8)
             (paint-cell 'hill
                         (+ (* i 200) (* cam-x 0.5)) 150 80 40)
             (loop (+ i 1))))
         (world/each 'ground
                     (lambda (t)
                       (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
         (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32))))))

(big-bang three-layer-parallax)
```

Note the simplification: for parallax layers, we pass a world-x of
`(offset) + (cam-x * rate)`. The runtime subtracts cam-x, giving
`(offset - cam-x * (1 - rate))`. When rate is 1.0 (foreground), the
layer moves in perfect step with camera-shift. When rate is 0.5
(mid), half. When rate is 0.2 (distant), one-fifth. When rate is 0
(sky), no motion at all.

Play it. The kid runs right. Ground streams past. Grass tips wave in
front (add wobble via `tick/sine` per tile). Hills roll gently. Distant
mountains barely stir. The sky sits still.

That is depth from motion. It costs perhaps twenty lines of paint code.

---

## 9.4 Parallax within a layer

You can vary parallax rate WITHIN a layer for even more depth cues.
Close mountains at 0.4, far mountains at 0.15. Or clouds at 0.7 (with
independent time-wind) so they drift even when the camera is still.

```scheme
;; Clouds that drift independently of camera motion.
(define cloud-time 0)

(define (moving-clouds)
  (world/reset!)
  (scene/grid 'ground 60 1 32 20 0 200)
  (world/each 'ground
              (lambda (t) (entity/shape! t 'rect 32 20) (entity/solid! t #t)))
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 100 168)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 16 32)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
    (world/camera-follow! p 0.1 60 40)
    (world/camera-bounds! 0 0 1920 240)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (set! cloud-time (+ cloud-time 0.5))
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (let ((cam-x (car (world/camera))))
         ;; Three clouds drifting.
         (let loop ((i 0))
           (when (< i 4)
             (let ((cloud-x (modulo (+ (* i 200)
                                        (* cam-x 0.3)
                                        (* cloud-time 0.4))
                                    1920)))
               (paint-cell 'cloud (+ cloud-x cam-x) 60 40 15))
             (loop (+ i 1))))
         (world/each 'ground
                     (lambda (t)
                       (paint-cell 'ground (entity/x t) (entity/y t) 32 20)))
         (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 16 32))))))

(big-bang moving-clouds)
```

The clouds drift right at 0.4 pixels per frame regardless of camera
motion, AND parallax at rate 0.3 with camera. `modulo` wraps them
around the world width so they always have something to show.

---

## 9.5 The four patterns in a scrolling world

**Composition.** Each layer is composed of position + parallax-rate +
paint. Chapter 8's world composition is base-layer only; this chapter
composes multiple parallax layers.

**Orchestration.** Paint order matters. Sky first (backmost). Then
mountains. Then hills. Then ground and entities. Then any UI overlay
last. If you paint in the wrong order, distant things cover close
things and the world looks broken.

**In-routing.** No new input routing.

**Routing.** The critical routing: WHICH cam-x offset each layer sees.
That is a routing table — layer -> parallax rate. Change the table,
change the depth.

---

## 9.6 Common desktop tasks

**Shop-page depth.** A shop's landing page can be a parallax scene:
background 'shop atmosphere' image at 0.2 rate, mid-layer product
categories at 0.6, foreground featured items at 1.0. As the customer
scrolls, the page gets depth. This is not a game — but it IS the same
paint routing.

**Receipt scrolling.** An order confirmation can scroll past like a
side-scroller — the receipt items pass in the foreground, brand imagery
in the mid, sky in back. Physics of a page turn done as parallax.

---

## 9.7 Pitfalls

**Layer flickers on scroll.** Your parallax rate isn't a clean
fraction of pixel positions and rounding causes jitter. Round to
integers per frame: `(round (* cam-x rate))`.

**Distant layer runs out.** Your sprites for the layer don't loop.
Wrap with `modulo` on the world width.

**Player disappears behind mountain.** Paint order — mountain painted
AFTER player. Reverse the order.

**Layer scrolls the wrong way.** You added instead of subtracted.
Parallax means slower motion IN THE SAME direction, not motion in the
opposite direction.

**Performance drops with too many layers.** Cap at 3-4 layers. Paint
only visible sprites (frustum-cull with `when` predicate).

---

## 9.8 Try this yourself

1. Add a fourth layer: fog just in front of the mountains, rate
   0.35, semi-transparent.
2. Add wind: shift the cloud drift with `tick/sine (* frame 0.01)`
   so clouds meander instead of moving in a straight line.
3. Vertical parallax: as the player jumps high, the mountains rise
   slightly. The horizon moves.
4. Time-of-day: swap sky color from blue to orange to purple over
   1000 frames. The parallax pieces don't move, but their palette
   does.
5. Depth-of-field: paint distant layer with smaller sprites and
   dimmer color (via `paint-glow` opposite).
6. A cave scene: everything inverse. Distant walls scroll faster
   than close walls, and near you feels big.

---

## 9.9 What we built

Multi-layer parallax with three rates. Cloud drift independent of
camera. Paint-order awareness. World-width wrapping for infinite
layers.

Next chapter: put enemies in this world that don't just drift — they
REACT. Chase you when close. Run away when hurt. Wander when idle.
Simple AI, arcade-style.")

